26/05/2009
Greek Foreign Minister Dora Bakoyannis met with Serbian counterpart Vuk Jeremic on Monday (May 25th) in Athens. They discussed Serbia's EU accession prospects, regional stability and bilateral economic issues. Jeremic emphasised the need for easing EU visa requirements for Serbia. Bakoyannis voiced Greece's steadfast support for the Balkan countries' economies -- in spite of the global economic crisis -- saying their development is a top priority. 
*** 
Turkish President Abdullah Gul began an official five-day visit to Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan on Tuesday (May 26th). Gul will meet with his Kyrygz and Tajik counterparts to discuss bilateral relations and regional and international matters. He is accompanied by State Minister Faruk Celik and Industry and Trade Minister Nihat Ergun. The Turkish-Kyrgyz and Turkish-Tajik Business Council will also hold meetings to sign several relevant bi-lateral agreements. 
*** 
Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) Presidency Chairman Nebojsa Radmanovic kicked-off an official visit to Serbia on Monday (May 25th). He is expected to hold talks with President Boris Tadic, Prime Minister Mirko Cvetkovic and Parliament Speaker Slavica Djukic-Dejanovic. 
*** 
US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton announced on Friday (May 22nd) she will visit Greece at the end of June to attend an OSCE meeting. Greece, which currently holds the OSCE chairmanship, is scheduled to host an informal meeting for the organisation's foreign ministers on June 27th and 28th, on the island of Corfu. 
*** 
 Hague war crimes tribunal chief prosecutor Serge Brammertz is visiting Croatia from Monday (May 25th) until Wednesday. Brammertz met on Monday with Deputy Prime Minister Jadranka Kosor in Zagreb to discuss the missing "artillery logs" which the tribunal seeks from Croatia to conduct trial proceedings against Ante Gotovina, Ivan Cermak and Mladen Markac. Kosor reassured Brammertz the Croatian government will make extra efforts to find the documents. As part of his visit, Brammertz will also attend a regional conference on war crimes on the island of Brijuni. 
*** 
Croatian Interior Minister Tomislav Karamarko and Serbian counterpart Ivica Dacic signed an agreement on police co-operation Monday (May 25th) in Rijeka, in an effort to boost the two countries' efforts against international organised crime. Dacic proposed establishing a regional centre against organised crime based in Belgrade. Karamarko praised the co-operation between the Croatian and the Serbian police services. The two ministers also signed an agreement on the joint battle against illegal immigration. 
*** 
Montenegrin President Filip Vujanovic conducted a two-day visit to Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) at the weekend. He met with members of the tripartite presidency, High Representative to BiH Valentin Inzko Inzko and Bosnian Serb leaders. 
(Various sources -- 19/05/09-26/05/09)  
